ting sociability and fertilizing his creative spirit. Walking up and down the winding pathways of Sorrento and drawing on Nietzsche's personal notebooks, D'Iorio tells the compelling story of Nietzsche's metamorphosis beneath the Italian skies. It was here, D'Iorio shows, that Nietzsche broke intellectually with Wagner, where he decided to leave his post at Bâle, and where he drafted his first work of aphorisms, Human, All Too Human, which ushered in his mature era. A sun-soaked account of a philosopher with a notoriously overcast disposition, this book is a surprising travelogue through southern Italy and the history of philosophy alike.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 4aFree Spirit. 4aFriedrich Wilhelm Nietzsche. 4aItaly. 4aSchopenhauer. 4aThings Human All Too Human. 4ahuman. 4ametaphysics. 4anatural science. 4apre-Platonic philosophers. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aGorelick, Sylvia Mae08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226288659423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226288659.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles